<style>
  :root{
    --bg:#0c0e1a;--bg-2:#11142a;--surface:#151829;--surface-2:#1a1e34;--border:#252a44;--border-soft:#1d2138;
    --gold:#c9a44c;--gold-soft:#8a7333;--gold-glow:rgba(201,164,76,.18);--oxblood:#7a2e2e;--burnt:#c97a3a;--moss:#6b8e5a;
    --bone:#e8e3d5;--bone-2:#c8c2b1;--mute:#7a8099;--mute-2:#565b76;
    --serif:'Fraunces','Iowan Old Style',Georgia,serif;--sans:'Inter',sans-serif;--mono:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;
  }
  *,*::before,*::after{box-sizing:border-box}
  body{margin:0;background:var(--bg);color:var(--bone);font-family:var(--sans);line-height:1.55;-webkit-font-smoothing:antialiased}
  ::selection{background:var(--gold);color:var(--bg)}
  body::before{content:'';position:fixed;inset:0;pointer-events:none;z-index:0;background:radial-gradient(ellipse 70% 50% at 50% -10%,rgba(201,164,76,.06),transparent 60%)}
  .wrap{max-width:840px;margin:0 auto;padding:0 28px;position:relative;z-index:1}
  .back{display:inline-block;margin:40px 0 0;font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px;letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--mute);text-decoration:none;border:1px solid var(--border);padding:11px 18px;transition:all .2s}
  .back:hover{color:var(--gold);border-color:var(--gold)}

  header{padding:46px 0 50px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-soft);margin-bottom:10px}
  .eyebrow{font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px;letter-spacing:.18em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--gold);display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:12px;margin-bottom:22px}
  .eyebrow::before{content:'';width:28px;height:1px;background:var(--gold)}
  h1{font-family:var(--serif);font-weight:300;font-size:clamp(36px,5.5vw,58px);line-height:1.04;letter-spacing:-.03em;margin:0 0 20px}
  h1 em{font-style:italic;color:var(--gold)}
  .lede{font-family:var(--serif);font-weight:300;font-size:19px;line-height:1.6;color:var(--bone-2);max-width:60ch}
  .neutral{display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:9px;font-family:var(--mono);font-size:10px;letter-spacing:.08em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--moss);margin-top:26px;border:1px solid var(--border);padding:9px 14px}
  .neutral .d{width:6px;height:6px;border-radius:50%;background:var(--moss);box-shadow:0 0 8px var(--moss)}

  section{padding:54px 0;border-top:1px solid var(--border-soft)}
  .sec-kicker{font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px;letter-spacing:.16em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--mute);margin-bottom:18px;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:12px}
  .sec-kicker .no{color:var(--gold)}
  h2{font-family:var(--serif);font-weight:300;font-size:30px;letter-spacing:-.02em;margin:0 0 16px;line-height:1.12}
  p{font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;color:var(--bone-2)}

  .dims{display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0;margin-top:24px;border-top:1px solid var(--border)}
  .dim{display:grid;grid-template-columns:30px 1fr;gap:20px;padding:20px 0;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-soft)}
  .dim-no{font-family:var(--mono);font-size:12px;color:var(--gold)}
  .dim-name{font-family:var(--serif);font-size:20px;color:var(--bone);margin-bottom:6px;letter-spacing:-.01em}
  .dim-def{font-size:14px;color:var(--bone-2);line-height:1.55}

  .rubric{width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin-top:20px;font-size:13px}
  .rubric th{font-family:var(--mono);font-size:9px;letter-spacing:.08em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--mute);text-align:left;padding:10px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border)}
  .rubric td{padding:12px 10px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-soft);color:var(--bone-2);line-height:1.5;vertical-align:top}
  .rubric .lvl{font-family:var(--mono);color:var(--gold);white-space:nowrap}

  .bands{display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(5,1fr);gap:8px;margin-top:22px}
  .band{border:1px solid var(--border);border-top:2px solid var(--gold-soft);padding:16px 14px;text-align:center}
  .band-l{font-family:var(--serif);font-size:24px;color:var(--gold)}
  .band-r{font-family:var(--mono);font-size:10px;color:var(--mute);margin-top:6px}
  .band-d{font-size:11px;color:var(--bone-2);margin-top:8px;line-height:1.4}

  .agents{display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(2,1fr);gap:8px;margin-top:22px}
  .agent{border:1px solid var(--border);border-left:2px solid var(--gold-soft);padding:13px 15px}
  .agent-n{font-family:var(--mono);font-size:11px;color:var(--gold);margin-bottom:4px}
  .agent-r{font-size:12px;color:var(--bone-2);line-height:1.45}

  .formula{font-family:var(--mono);font-size:13px;color:var(--bone);background:var(--surface);border:1px solid var(--border);border-left:2px solid var(--gold);padding:18px 20px;margin:18px 0;line-height:1.7}
  .formula .c{color:var(--gold)}
  .limit{display:grid;grid-template-columns:24px 1fr;gap:14px;padding:14px 0;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-soft)}
  .limit-i{color:var(--burnt);font-family:var(--mono);font-size:12px}
  .limit-t{font-size:14px;color:var(--bone-2);line-height:1.55}
  footer{padding:40px 0 80px;font-family:var(--mono);font-size:10px;letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--mute-2)}
  footer span{color:var(--gold)}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<div class="wrap">
  <a class="back" href="index.html">&larr; Back to project</a>

  <header style="margin-top:30px">
    <div class="eyebrow">AEI Score · methodology · v1.0</div>
    <h1>How AEI scores a company &mdash; <em>and how to check it.</em></h1>
    <p class="lede">The AEI Score is a single, peer-relative measure of how well-positioned a company is to make its highest-stakes strategic decisions. This document is the customer-neutral framework: the six dimensions, the rubric, how scores aggregate into bands, how the agent ensemble and confidence work, and where the method stops.</p>
    <div class="neutral"><span class="d"></span>Customer-neutral · the same rubric is applied to every company</div>
  </header>

  <section>
    <div class="sec-kicker"><span class="no">01</span> The six dimensions</div>
    <h2>What we score</h2>
    <p>Every company is scored on the same six dimensions. Each is rated 1&ndash;5 against observable behaviours &mdash; never opinion &mdash; and the six roll up into one aggregate.</p>
    <div class="dims">
      <div class="dim"><div class="dim-no">D1</div><div><div class="dim-name">Strategic Vision</div><div class="dim-def">Clarity and testability of the strategic position. Is there a sharp, falsifiable claim about where value is created — or a portfolio of slogans?</div></div></div>
      <div class="dim"><div class="dim-no">D2</div><div><div class="dim-name">Talent &amp; Model</div><div class="dim-def">Depth and resilience of the people-and-operating model behind the strategy, including exposure to structural shifts such as automation.</div></div></div>
      <div class="dim"><div class="dim-no">D3</div><div><div class="dim-name">Capital Discipline</div><div class="dim-def">How deliberately capital is allocated and reallocated. Does spend follow stated priorities, and is low-return spend retired?</div></div></div>
      <div class="dim"><div class="dim-no">D4</div><div><div class="dim-name">Technical Substrate</div><div class="dim-def">The defensibility and coherence of the technical and product foundation underpinning the strategy.</div></div></div>
      <div class="dim"><div class="dim-no">D5</div><div><div class="dim-name">Market Conviction</div><div class="dim-def">Category position and how the market and analysts read the company, relative to its constructed peer cohort.</div></div></div>
      <div class="dim"><div class="dim-no">D6</div><div><div class="dim-name">Execution Discipline</div><div class="dim-def">The cadence and follow-through of decisions: are strategic calls made, logged, sequenced and revisited?</div></div></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="sec-kicker"><span class="no">02</span> The rubric</div>
    <h2>1 to 5, by observable behaviour</h2>
    <p>Each dimension is scored against the same five-level scale. The examples below are illustrative of Capital Discipline; every dimension has its own behavioural anchors.</p>
    <table class="rubric">
      <thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Observable behaviour (example · Capital Discipline)</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="lvl">5 · Exemplary</td><td>Capital tracks stated priorities within tolerance; low-return programmes retired promptly; reallocation is routine and evidenced.</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="lvl">4 · Strong</td><td>Mostly disciplined; occasional lag between signal and reallocation; few legacy programmes persist.</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="lvl">3 · Adequate</td><td>Allocation broadly rational but slow; some material spend unattributed to return.</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="lvl">2 · Weak</td><td>Spend and stated strategy visibly diverge; low-return programmes persist past evidence.</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="lvl">1 · Critical</td><td>No discernible link between allocation and priorities; sustained spend on retired theses.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="sec-kicker"><span class="no">03</span> Aggregation &amp; bands</div>
    <h2>From six scores to one band</h2>
    <div class="formula">AEI Score = <span class="c">Σ</span> ( dimension<sub>i</sub> × weight<sub>i</sub> ) &nbsp;·&nbsp; weights default equal, re-weighted per sector profile.<br/>Band = peer-relative placement of the aggregate within the constructed cohort.</div>
    <p>The aggregate is then placed into a band &mdash; <b>peer-relative, not absolute</b>. A 3.4 is "Above-Peer" only against the right cohort; the same number could read differently elsewhere.</p>
    <div class="bands">
      <div class="band"><div class="band-l">A</div><div class="band-r">4.2–5.0</div><div class="band-d">Leading</div></div>
      <div class="band"><div class="band-l">B</div><div class="band-r">3.2–4.1</div><div class="band-d">Above-Peer</div></div>
      <div class="band"><div class="band-l">C</div><div class="band-r">2.5–3.1</div><div class="band-d">Mid-Maturity</div></div>
      <div class="band"><div class="band-l">D</div><div class="band-r">1.8–2.4</div><div class="band-d">Below-Peer</div></div>
      <div class="band"><div class="band-l">E</div><div class="band-r">1.0–1.7</div><div class="band-d">At-Risk</div></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="sec-kicker"><span class="no">04</span> Peer cohort</div>
    <h2>How the cohort is built</h2>
    <p>Every score is relative, so the cohort matters as much as the rubric. Cohorts are constructed from sector, scale, business-model and decision-frequency similarity &mdash; not market-cap alone &mdash; and are held stable quarter to quarter so movement is comparable. A company can request the cohort construction and challenge its members; reconstruction is itself a logged decision.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="sec-kicker"><span class="no">05</span> The 14-agent ensemble</div>
    <h2>Specialist reasoning, on the record</h2>
    <p>Each dimension is informed by specialist agents. Every agent leaves a finding in the reasoning trail of every decision &mdash; which is what makes a recommendation auditable rather than a black box.</p>
    <div class="agents">
      <div class="agent"><div class="agent-n">PORTFOLIO</div><div class="agent-r">Initiative count, overlap, fragmentation versus peer median.</div></div>
      <div class="agent"><div class="agent-n">CAPITAL</div><div class="agent-r">Spend-to-priority tracking; unattributed spend; ROI buckets.</div></div>
      <div class="agent"><div class="agent-n">PEER</div><div class="agent-r">Analogous moves across the cohort and their outcomes.</div></div>
      <div class="agent"><div class="agent-n">TALENT</div><div class="agent-r">Model resilience, automation exposure, key-person risk.</div></div>
      <div class="agent"><div class="agent-n">MARKET</div><div class="agent-r">Category position and analyst sentiment.</div></div>
      <div class="agent"><div class="agent-n">GOVERNANCE</div><div class="agent-r">Decision authority, vote requirements, legal timelines.</div></div>
      <div class="agent"><div class="agent-n">MODEL</div><div class="agent-r">Revenue-model exposure and structural shifts.</div></div>
      <div class="agent"><div class="agent-n">+ 7 more</div><div class="agent-r">Supply, energy, network, IP, workforce, risk and a synthesis agent.</div></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="sec-kicker"><span class="no">06</span> Confidence</div>
    <h2>Every score carries a confidence</h2>
    <p>Confidence (0&ndash;1) reflects source completeness, peer-precedent strength, and agent consensus. A high score with low confidence is flagged as such; a decision is only put forward when value-adjusted confidence clears the threshold. Dissenting agents are footnoted, never hidden.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="sec-kicker"><span class="no">07</span> Limitations</div>
    <h2>Where the method stops</h2>
    <div class="limit"><div class="limit-i">01</div><div class="limit-t">AEI scores positioning to <i>make</i> decisions well; it does not guarantee outcomes, which depend on execution outside the model.</div></div>
    <div class="limit"><div class="limit-i">02</div><div class="limit-t">Scores are only as current as the underlying sources; a weekly cadence means a 7-day worst-case latency.</div></div>
    <div class="limit"><div class="limit-i">03</div><div class="limit-t">Peer-relativity means a band reflects the cohort; a different defensible cohort can shift the band.</div></div>
    <div class="limit"><div class="limit-i">04</div><div class="limit-t">The method surfaces and quantifies decisions; the board decides. AEI is decision support, not a decision-maker.</div></div>
  </section>

  <footer>AEI Score Methodology · v1.0 · Genotwin GmbH · <span>customer-neutral framework</span></footer>
